foliation.p: Modern partial foliation in pencil, in the second part an added attempt to correct foliation in brown ink:
foliation.note: Numbering in pencil in the upper right-hand corner of the first rectos of each quire only. The foliator made an error at the beginning of quire 16, which ought to be f. 121. However, they marked it as f. 129, and the error is compounded in the beginning of quire 17 (f. 137) and quire 18 (f. 145).
An earlier hand writing in brown ink foliated all the pages for quires 17 and 18, the surving numbering starts from f. 127 (ff. 127-142) (current ff. 137-152).

binding.p: A 19th-century binding, fully bound in calf over mill-board with matching decoration in blind to left and right covers. Covers are each decorated with two concentric triple-fillet frames, the outer frame set at the perimeter of the boards, and the inner frame inset by 20 mm. Each corner of the inner frame is joined to the nearest corner of the outer frame with a triple fillet. Decorative archaded fleur-de-lis roll applied in blind to cover material over the head, fore, and tail edges of the boards.

Five raised bands on the spine. Spine compartments are decorated along their upper and lower perimeters with a triple fillet. Title label applied in black leather with the title Viaticus et morbis de alia tooled in gold. Two small printed paper labels affixed to spine 49 and 97. Brown and white head and tail bands.

acquisition.p: At Gonville and Caius College probably by 1600: perhaps recorded as no. 15 in the Ecloga Oxonio-Cantabrigiensis by Thomas James (1600).
It was there certainly by 1697 when Edward Bernard recorded it as no. 956 in the Catalogi Manuscriptorum Angliae (1697).

recordHist.source: This catalogue entry draws on Montague Rhodes James, A Descriptive Catalogue of the Manuscripts in the Library of Gonville and Caius College, 2 vols. (Cambridge, 1907-1908) vol. 1, pp. 96-97.

layout.seg: Frame and line ruled in leadpoint, at times almost invisible. Written in two columns, 42-56 lines to the page, below top line. Seven vertical bounding lines extending the full height of the page. A double horizontal line in the upper margin, and a single horizontal line in the lower margin of the page extending the full width of the page. Two line ruling for headings in the upper margin above the written columns.
Pricked in the outer, upper and lower margins.

decoNote.p: 6-line initial with penwork flourishing on f. 1r.
Two and three line initials alternating in red and blue with penwork flourishing in the other colour throught the volume.
Rubrication in the body of the text. Red and blue Roman numerals I-VII as page headings.
